07441nam a22011055i 9783110682588DE-B159720230228015514.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020934820  a97831106825887 a10.1515/97831106825882doi  a(DE-B1597)539350  a(OCoLC)1183855278  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aP134b.N46 202000aNew Approaches to Contrastive Linguistics :bEmpirical and Methodological Challenges /ced. by Renata Enghels, Marlies Jansegers, Bart Defrancq. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (V, 312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs [TiLSM] ,x1861-4302 ;v33600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tReflections on the use of data and methods in contrastive linguistics -- tA roadmap towards determining the universal status of semantic frames -- tQuantitative methods for corpus-based contrastive linguistics -- tOn the usefulness of comparable and parallel corpora for contrastive linguistics. Testing the semantic stability hypothesis -- tIs German more nominal than English? Evidence from a translation corpus -- tUsing data from simultaneous interpreting in contrastive linguistics -- tWH-ever in German, Dutch and English: a contrastive study showcasing the ConverGENTiecorpus -- tComparing corrective constructions: Contrastive negation in parallel and monolingual data -- tContrasting semantic fields across languages0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe practice of comparing languages has a long tradition characterized by a cyclic pattern of interest. Its meeting with corpus linguistics in the 1990s has led to a new sub-discipline of corpus-based contrastive studies. The present volume tackles two main challenges that had not yet been fully addressed in the literature, namely an empirical assessment of the nature of the data commonly used in cross-linguistic studies (e.g. translation data versus comparable data), and the development of advanced methods and statistical techniques suitably adapted to contrastive research settings. The papers collected in this volume endeavour to find out what (new) types of data are most useful for what kind of contrastive questions, and which advanced statistical techniques are most suited to deal with the multidimensionality of contrastive research questions. Answers to these questions are provided through the contrastive analysis of various language pairs or groups, and a wide variety of phenomena situated at almost all linguistic levels. In sum, this book provides an update on new methodological and theoretical insights in empirical contrastive linguistics and will stimulate further research within this field.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aContrastive linguistics.  aContrastive Linguistics.  aCorpus.  aInterpreting.  aTranslation.  aTypology.1 aBoas, Hans C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBossuyt, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollard, Camille, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Baets, Pauline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Sutter, Gert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDefrancq, Bart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDefrancq, Bart, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEnghels, Renata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnghels, Renata, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGries, Stefan Th., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator